## Why This Is Asked
This question probes practical IPC path design, per-core locality optimization, and safe buffer migration under memory pressure in high-performance systems.

## Key Concepts
- **Per-core allocator**: Each CPU core maintains a local free-list of buffers to minimize cache-line bouncing and lock contention
- **Lock-free CAS synchronization**: Compare-and-swap operations enable atomic updates without global locks
- **Cross-core buffer migration**: Moving buffers between cores to balance load while maintaining locality
- **Quotas and fairness**: Ensuring no single client monopolizes buffer resources

## Code Example
```c
// Minimal sketch (C-like) for acquire_buffer and migrate_buffer
typedef struct buf { 
    int id; 
    int state; 
    struct buf *next; 
} buf_t;

typedef struct core_pool { 
    buf_t *free; 
    atomic_int quota; 
} core_pool_t;

buf_t *acquire_buffer(int core) {
    core_pool_t *p = &pools[core];
    buf_t *b;
    do {
        b = atomic_load(&p->free);
        if (!b) return NULL;
    } while (!atomic_compare_exchange_weak(&p->free, &b, b->next));
    atomic_fetch_sub(&p->quota, 1);
    return b;
}

void migrate_buffer(buf_t *b, int to_core) {
    core_pool_t *p = &pools[to_core];
    buf_t *old_head;
    do {
        old_head = atomic_load(&p->free);
        b->next = old_head;
    } while (!atomic_compare_exchange_weak(&p->free, &old_head, b));
}
```

