## Minimal Pseudo-Code

```javascript
// Enqueue: add request to per-container queue, attempt to acquire device ticket
function enqueue(container_id, request) {
  container_queue = get_container_queue(container_id)
  container_queue.push(request)

  // Try to acquire dispatch token for this container
  if (container_credits[container_id] > 0) {
    device_queue = get_device_queue(request.device)
    if (device_queue.try_acquire_lock(container_id)) {
      dispatch(container_id, request.device)
    }
  }
}

// Dispatch: select next request using DRR, respecting weights and deficits
function dispatch(container_id, device) {
  device_queue = get_device_queue(device)

  // DRR: serve quantum, carry deficit to next round
  while (device_queue.has_pending(container_id)) {
    quantum = container_weight[container_id] * base_quantum
    deficit[container_id] += quantum

    while (deficit[container_id] > 0 && !container_queue.empty(container_id)) {
      request = container_queue.pop(container_id)
      service_time = estimate_cost(request)
      deficit[container_id] -= service_time
      issue_to_device(device, request)
    }

    // Move to next container if depleted
    container_id = device_queue.next_container(container_id)
  }
}

// Budget reclaimer: periodic task to reclaim unused credits
function reclaim_credits() {
  for each container in active_containers {
    if (idle_time[container] > idle_bonus_threshold) {
      container_credits[container] += idle_bonus
    }
    // Burn-in period for newly activated containers
    container_credits[container] = min(
      container_credits[container] + base_allocation,
      max_burst_limit
    )
  }
}
```

## Overview
This question evaluates understanding of inter-thread synchronization, producer-consumer patterns, and low-level data structure design in operating system environments.

## Key Concepts
- Circular buffer with head/tail indices and wraparound handling
- Mutexes and condition variables for blocking operations and wakeups
- Memory visibility guarantees via compiler and hardware memory barriers
- Correctness and performance characteristics with multiple concurrent producers

## Code Example
```c
typedef struct {
    char data[LOG_SIZE];
    int valid;
} slot_t;

slot_t buffer[N];
int head = 0;
int tail = 0;
int count = 0;

mutex_t mtx;
cond_t not_full;
cond_t not_empty;

void enqueue(const char *record) {
    mutex_lock(&mtx);
    while (count >= N)
        cond_wait(&not_full, &mtx);
    buffer[tail % N] = *(slot_t *)record;
    tail++;
    count++;
    cond_signal(&not_empty);
    mutex_unlock(&mtx);
}

void dequeue(char *record) {
    mutex_lock(&mtx);
    while (count == 0)
        cond_wait(&not_empty, &mtx);
    *(slot_t *)record = buffer[head % N];
    head++;
    count--;
    cond_signal(&not_full);
    mutex_unlock(&mtx);
}
```

## Test Plan
1. **Correctness**: Verify no data loss or corruption with single producer/consumer
2. **Blocking**: Confirm enqueue blocks when buffer is full, dequeue blocks when empty
3. **Throughput**: Measure records/second with 1, 4, 8, and 16 concurrent producers
4. **Stress**: Run sustained test to detect race conditions and memory leaks

