## Why This Is Asked

Tests understanding of on-demand stack growth via page faults, guard pages, and race-free allocation. It mirrors real kernel tasks where stacks grow dynamically and multiple threads may fault near boundaries.

## Key Concepts

- Page fault handling for stack growth
- Guard page utilization and overflow protection
- Atomic coordination to avoid double-growth races
- Per-thread stack state updates and TLB consistency

## Code Example

```c
// Sketch: stack growth on fault
int handle_stack_fault(struct thread *th, uintptr_t fault_addr) {
  // assume downward-growing stack with base at th->stack_base and limit th->stack_limit
  if (fault_addr < th->stack_base - th->stack_size_limit) return -EFAULT;
  uintptr_t page = PAGE_ALIGNED(fault_addr);
  // claim growth; if another thread grew it, just map after retry
  if (!atomic_test_and_set(&th->growth_flag, page)) {
    void *p = allocate_page();
    if (!p) { atomic_clear(&th->growth_flag, page); return -ENOMEM; }
    map_page(th, page, p);
  }
  // update bounds and flush TLB as needed
  th->stack_limit = min(th->stack_limit, page + PAGE_SIZE);
  tlb_flush_page(th, page);
  return 0;
}
```

